body:
When I create an endpoint that validates path params

```nodejs
import { validator } from "hono-openapi/zod";

const todos = new Hono();

todos.get(
  "/:id",
  describeRoute({
    description: "Get a single todo",
  }),
  validator("param", z.object({ id: z.string().uuid() })),
  async (c) => {
    const id = c.req.valid("param").id;
  }
)
```

Then the openapi JSON generated includes 2 objects for `id`. One in path and the other in param.
```
...
"parameters": [
          {
            "schema": {
              "type": "string"
            },
            "in": "path",
            "name": "id",
            "required": true
          },
          {
            "in": "param",
            "name": "id",
            "schema": {
              "type": "string",
              "format": "uuid"
            },
            "required": true
          }
        ]
...
```

Which then breaks the scalar UI and I am unable to try any requests due to this error
```
{
  "_errors": [],
  "parameters": {
    "1": {
      "_errors": [],
      "in": {
        "_errors": [
          "Invalid enum value. Expected 'path' | 'query' | 'header' | 'cookie', received 'param'"
        ]
      }
    },
    "_errors": []
  }
}
```

Given a route with a validator:

```ts
validator(
  'query',
  z.object({
    a: z.number({ coerce: true }),
    b: z.number({ coerce: true }).optional(),
  }),
)
```

the spec will produce:

```json
"parameters": [
  {
    "in": "query",
    "name": "a",
    "schema": {
      "type": "number"
    }
  },
  {
    "in": "query",
    "name": "b",
    "schema": {
      "type": "number"
    }
  }
]
```

The expected output is:
```diff
 "parameters": [
   {
     "in": "query",
     "name": "a",
+    "required": true,
     "schema": {
       "type": "number"
     }
   },
   {
     "in": "query",
     "name": "b",
     "schema": {
       "type": "number"
     }
   }
 ]
```

This looks like a simple fix because the resolved schema from `zod-openapi` correctly includes `required: ["a"]`, so we just need to check that when constructing the parameter spec.

Hi @MathurAditya724 When using hono-openapi with a Hono app typed with Env, the openAPISpecs function does not accept app as an argument, resulting in an error or unexpected behavior. The Env type includes specific bindings, which may be causing this issue.

```typescript
type Env = {
  Bindings: {
    MY_VAR: string;
  };
};

const app = new Hono<Env>;

app.get(
  "/openapi",
  openAPISpecs(app, {
    documentation: {
      info: {
        title: "Hono",
        version: "1.0.0",
        description: "API for greeting users",
      }
    },
  })
);
```

